text:
No, Gura, you're not in the wrong here.

This game just looses its grip after a while, making clear mistakes.

Once you get into the ship, everything becomes way too humanized to hold much mystery. Plus, everything there is so bright and blue - blue being a very calming color. The environment absolutely suffers in design at times. The story is so overbearing, constantly pulling you away from the controls, which helps to ruin emersion in gaming horror experiences.

But... worst of all:

The monsters are just... no threat. Once you learn you can outrun their hobble and easily loose them, they become a joke. Not only that, if they grab you... you'll be fine. They'll just scream "boo I'm gross" and you'll get away, one way or another. That's really lame. Put that next to Alien, Isolation, where the alien is extremely fast, strong, smart... and if it grabs you, YOU'RE DEAD. It makes the game extremely intense, keeping you on your toes! Rebirth? The only thing putting me anywhere on my toes was the cheap jump-scare flashes.

So yeah, I'm disappointed too, Gura.

Now go play Alien Isolation. :)

The approach of running trough the game with the attention span of a shark works better when the game is action-oriented (think Outlast, Dark Deception and Resident Evil) so I think that Amnesia: Rebirth might not be the best streaming material.

text:
@LetsShitPost  SOMA's horror was in the existential dread of its story, combined with the terrifying nature of the ocean.

TDD's horror was the perfect amount of Lovecraft and the realistic portrayal of human behaviour and sanity.

A Machine for Pigs had its horror solely on the plot, which is great by itself but falls short as an actual game.

For Rebirth...I don't know, honestly. It feels like they tried to do the first 3 but crammed it all together without breathing space.
author: @juicejooos

text:
@juicejooos  Yeah completely agree with you. In the dev commentary they mentioned that they tried combining the best of SOMA''s linear narrative with the best of Amnesia TDD horror and gameplay. It's pretty clear they tried to do that but they failed to hit both marks and ended up with a mediocre version of both. Even SOMA's non-narrative horror and atmosphere was much scarier than Rebirth. 

I don't know what exactly was wrong with Rebirth compared to the Original, but if I had to pinpoint it it's probably its really bad pacing and it's feeling of being a walking simulator in a theme park. Like the amount of times the game takes away control of the player for its slow ass un-skippable cutscenes is so, so frustrating. You rarely ever want to remove control from your player in a horror game because you'd then remove player choice, which is incredibly important in immersive genres like horror games. You can even see Gura being frustrated with the cutscenes in game. It just messes with the entire pacing of the game and makes you feel more frustrated than scared in most situations. TDD also takes away some control in narrative situations but you could still move and look around. The cheap jpg jumpscares also doesn't help that frustration either. It's incredibly annoying after the first 3-5 and takes away any tension there was. Also, the amount of fucking cheap jumpscares in this game feels so unlike Frictional Games, I really don't know what they were thinking. In the first Amnesia, I can count literally only ONE intended jumpscare and is still imo one of the best uses of jump scares in any horror game.

text:
I think it was really good, but I can see why people could think otherwise. Some direct-plot elements seem inconsequential, story presentation is interruptive to the gameplay and neither depth of the strory nor scares are maximized. It unilizes its themes and is quite effective as a lingering feeling, also for me it was consistently tense. But here for a change the gameplay interrupted the story, making you less engaged since there was too many setpieces, and you knew that if you push throught the game will make sure that you are safe in the end. So despite requiring a cetain amount of immersion it constantly interupted both an emotional engagement and gameplay engagement at once; coincidentally not delivering too strongly on neiter horror nor story front. 
Still it's more sophisticated than most games, setting to do something more than just "wow" the audience or "just" be scary. I'd say it's nor really made for streaming, since it requires some focus and suspension of disbelief, while also being very distracting itself. I certainly appreciate Frictiona;'s effort and the fact that they didn't just set out to please the audience with a samey game - I think they will now be better of discontinuing Amnesia and creating thematically coherent horrors from scratch.

Still enjoy some Gura, but I think that evaluating this game through either streaming or watching a stream will make some of its strenghts go unnoticed; even if many complaints are definitely correct.

text: @AkiRa22084  When you're playing a game that relies on immersion like Amnesia or most horror games and one of the game's "horror" mechanic is the meta act of losing progress because of death, then the game is definitely doing something wrong. The first Amnesia was one of the most groundbreaking horror games and there was absolutely no penalty for death. Hell, the player was actually rewarded for death because the monsters stopped roaming after you die. What most players are afraid of isn't death when facing a monster, it's the unknown, the chase, and everything built up around the death. What usually happens when a player gets caught and dies is that all the tension wears off because the player is already experiencing the worst thing that can happen that's out of their control. It's pretty much a reset button for tension if you think about it.
author: @loop_zoop

text:
@loop_zoop  Reset for tension is a good thing. If the fear is there all the time then you get used to it. It needs to have ups and downs. Yes you get a breather after you die but the fear grows for the next encounter if you lost a lot. The first Slenderman game became a phenomenon for a reason.
The first Amnesia was mocked when people figured out how easy it was to troll it's AI. They called the monster Homer Simpson back in the day.
author: @AkiRa22084

text:
​ @AkiRa22084  If you die or lose your progress you will end up encountering the monster again, but now with the knowledge of knowing the monster's pattern and how they kill. In Slenderman people weren't afraid of loss of progress at all, they were afraid of all of the mechanics leading up to death. What ended up often happening was the player for the first few times they play didn't know how the monster works or what exactly will happen when they are caught, the tension and fear is still there. However, when they die, they now have even more knowledge of how Slendy kills and they see its face so much of the mystery and tension is gone. Dieing and losing progress just allows a player to better their strategy and optimize their routes even more, pretty much giving the player more agency. That's what I remembered when I played that game.

The first amnesia it was very difficult to figure out the monster's ai for most people if you went in blind and didn't try to actively metagame. Like yeah of course it was very easily to troll around if you knew how the ai works if you read it online or try to actively break the game but that's not really what the game is about. The intention of removing the monster after death is to let the player not get used to how the monster works in the environment they're in. You let them progress through an environment they've already died in, then when they've moved on to another area, spawn the monster there and now they're in a new environment with the monster they've just were getting used to. When they despawn the monster and let them progress they basically "hide" its behavior for the next encounter. It's also why I think there was a new monster midway through the game. It was a very effective smoke and mirrors tactic that made the very simple ai seem more unpredictable than it really was. 

That said, with how most people play games nowadays, I don't think that works as well as it does anymore. If an ai is dumb enough, players will probably notice. But the idea of keeping encounters short to keep monsters unpredictable still rings true and resetting progress as a failstate is not a good way of keeping encounters short nor keeping a player on their toes.
